  "opening_lines": [
    {
      "line": 1,
      "text": "TOOLS & IDEAS"
    },
    {
      "line": 4,
      "text": "Tree-Free Paper"
    },
    {
      "line": 7,
      "text": "Making Health"
    },
    {
      "line": 11,
      "text": "No. 80 |"
    },
    {
      "line": 12,
      "text": "Fall 1993 | |"
    },
    {
      "line": 14,
      "text": "($7.50 Canadian) 7099239594 III , |"
    },
    {
      "line": 17,
      "text": "HAT HAPPENED ON PAGE 93 OF THE LAST ISSUE? And what's"
    },
    {
      "line": 18,
      "text": "the deal with Gossip? We'll deal with Gossip in Gossip. Suffice it to"
    },
    {
      "line": 19,
      "text": "say here that the “censorship” of Gossip was a deliberate joke that"
    },
    {
      "line": 22,
      "text": "took on a different meaning weeks after it was composed."
    },
    {
      "line": 25,
      "text": "The censorship of this magazine by its printer, Publishers Press of Louisville,"
    },
    {
      "line": 28,
      "text": "Kentucky, was not a joke, however."
    },
    {
      "line": 31,
      "text": "Stewart Brand was the guest editor. I have to thank Stewart"
    },
    {
      "line": 34,
      "text": "for taking the time to edit an issue, to enable me to finish a"
    },
    {
      "line": 37,
      "text": "book, at the same time that he was trying to finish a book him-"
    },
    {
      "line": 38,
      "text": "What happened to"
    },
    {
      "line": 41,
      "text": "self. Stewart picked an excerpt for a review of Paul Krassner’s"
    },
    {
      "line": 42,
      "text": "Whol e E a rth Revi eW Realist that truthfully reflected the typical content of the Real-"
    },
    {
      "line": 44,
      "text": "ist. Many people find the Realist offensive. The cartoon that"
    },
    {
      "line": 45,
      "text": "Issue #79"
    },
    {
      "line": 48,
      "text": "was picked is one that many people would find offensive: a"
    },
    {
      "line": 51,
      "text": "caricature of Woody Allen entering Mia Farrow’s house,"
    },
    {
      "line": 52,
      "text": "with the caption “Honey, I fucked the kids.”"
    },
    {
      "line": 55,
      "text": "The issue had been in the printer’s hands for several days when our art"
    },
    {
      "line": 56,
      "text": "director, Kathleen O'Neill, received a telephone call from a representative"
    },
    {
      "line": 58,
      "text": "of Publishers Press. He said that he had been trying to get in touch with Stewart"
    },
    {
      "line": 59,
      "text": "Brand (who was by then sequestered in a cabin in Northern California, finish-"
    },
    {
      "line": 60,
      "text": "ing his book on “how buildings learn”). The president of Publishers Press was"
    },
    {
      "line": 63,
      "text": "“suggesting” that we not run the excerpt from the Realist. We were scheduled"
    },
    {
      "line": 66,
      "text": "to go to press in a matter of days. Subsequent conver-"
    },
    {
      "line": 67,
      "text": "sations with representatives of Publishers Press made it"
    },
    {
      "line": 68,
      "text": "clear that the suggestion was more than a suggestion:"
    },
    {
      "line": 69,
      "text": "the employees of the printer strongly objected to the"
    },
    {
      "line": 70,
      "text": "cartoon and the printer would rather lose our business"
    },
    {
      "line": 71,
      "text": "than print it. Kathleen got in touch with Stewart."
    },
    {
      "line": 72,
      "text": "Stewart said it was my call. Which it was."
    },
    {
      "line": 75,
      "text": "This incident couldn’t have happened at a more"
    },
    {
      "line": 77,
      "text": "critical time. We've been losing money for many years"
    },
    {
      "line": 78,
